<paragraph id="E97036DD3F18FF8FFF76F9F2FE1EF96F" blockId="45.[151,1437,1652,2039]" box="[151,510,1652,1679]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Size. Reaches 
<quantity id="2E379B383F18FF8FFEDBF9F3FE91F96E" box="[314,369,1653,1679]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" unit="cm" value="7.0">7 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F18FF8CFF26F91EFF0EFE6B" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F18FF8FFF26F91EFACFF887" blockId="45.[151,1437,1652,2039]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Morphology. D VI + I,10–11; A I,9–10; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F18FF8FFD68F91EFB2CF953" bold="true" box="[649,1228,1688,1715]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">P 16–18, the uppermost 2 rays free of membrane</emphasis>
. Body moderately elongate, the depth 
<quantity id="2E379B383F18FF8FFE92F93AFE05F937" box="[371,485,1724,1751]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2446" metricValueMax="1.397" metricValueMin="1.0921999999999998" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" unit="in" value="4.9" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="4.3">4.3–5.5 in</quantity>
standard length. Head subcylindrical, with a short rounded snout. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F18FF8FFB31F93AFCB8F91B" bold="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">The second spine of first dorsal fin longest, with very short filament in males</emphasis>
. Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. Pelvic fins united to form a disc. Caudal fin rounded, shorter than head. Scales ctenoid to below origin of first dorsal fin, cycloid ventrally on abdomen, no scales on head, chest, predorsal and prepectoral areas. Scales visible on dead specimens by reticulate pattern of pigmentation along scale edges, visibility on live specimens unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F18FF8CFF26F8F6FB1EFF50" blockId="45.[151,1437,1652,2039]" lastBlockId="46.[151,1436,150,394]" lastPageId="46" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Fresh coloration. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F18FF8FFE6CF8F6FF09F84F" bold="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Greenish or brownish gray, scale edges dark brown, scales on lower body outlined with orange</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F18FF8FFF1BF812FEB0F84E" box="[250,336,1940,1967]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1404,1428]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-120@46.[151,1436,417,1381]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 50. Freshly dead coloration of Coryogalops ocheticus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Gulf of Suez, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601725/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
); a series of indistinct light brown blotches along back, the first on nape, ending at origin of first dorsal fin; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F18FF8FFEF3F83EFC24F833" bold="true" box="[274,964,1976,2002]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">side of body with a series of 7 indistinct blackish blotches</emphasis>
; head with three blackish spots or double spots below eye, 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F18FF8FFE82F85AFC7EF817" bold="true" box="[355,926,2012,2038]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">side of head with irregular small orange spots</emphasis>
; first dorsal fin with 2 or 3 curved oblique crossbands; pectoral fins with 2 blackish spots at base; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFCE0FF10FC05FF51" bold="true" box="[769,997,150,176]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">pelvic fins blackish</emphasis>
(visible also on 
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F1BFF8CFB7FFF11FB11FF50" box="[1182,1265,150,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="46.[151,250,1404,1428]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,417,1381]" captionTargetId="figure-120@46.[151,1436,417,1381]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="FIGURE 50. Freshly dead coloration of Coryogalops ocheticus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Gulf of Suez, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601725/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1BFF8CFF26FF3DFBA6FF34" blockId="46.[151,1436,150,394]" box="[199,1094,187,213]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Similar species. 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F1BFF8CFE9EFF3DFD29FF34" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Kolombatovic" baseAuthorityYear="1891" box="[383,713,187,213]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Millerigobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrocephalus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFE9EFF3DFD29FF34" box="[383,713,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Millerigobius macrocephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F1BFF8CFD36FF3DFC95FF34" authorityName="Benthic" baseAuthorityName="Risso" baseAuthorityYear="1827" box="[727,885,187,213]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zebrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zebrus">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFD36FF3DFC95FF34" box="[727,885,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Zebrus zebrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="2ECF4D5E3F1BFF8CFC62FF3DFBDFFF34" authorityName="Kovacic, Sanda &amp; Vukic" authorityYear="2021" box="[899,1087,187,213]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gobiidae" genus="Zebrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pallaoroi">
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFC62FF3DFBDFFF34" box="[899,1087,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Zebrus pallaoroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1BFF8CFF26FF59FA6CFF18" blockId="46.[151,1436,150,394]" box="[199,1420,222,249]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Habitat. Inhabits shallow water, isolated hard substrate but found occasionally on sand bottom (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F1BFF8CFB14FF59FA9FFF18" author="Goren, M." box="[1269,1407,222,249]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" pagination="1 - 99" refId="ref55474" refString="Goren, M. (1985) A review of the gobiid fish genus Monishia Smith, 1949, from the western Indian Ocean and Red Sea, with description of a new species. Contributions in Science, 360, 1 - 99. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / p. 208179" type="journal article" year="1985">Goren 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1BFF8CFF26FE85FF0EFE6B" blockId="46.[151,1436,150,394]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Geographic distribution. Reported from the Red Sea: 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F1BFF8CFCC2FE85FC86FEFC" box="[803,870,259,285]" name="Egypt" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Egypt</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="2B0BF83F3F1BFF8CFC94FE85FC4DFEFC" box="[885,941,259,285]" country="Egypt" name="As Suways" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Suez</collectingRegion>
Canal, Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="2B0BF83F3F1BFF8CFBBFFE85FB77FEFC" box="[1118,1175,259,285]" country="Egypt" name="As Suways" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Suez</collectingRegion>
, and Ras Muhammad), 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F1BFF8CFF76FEA1FECAFEA0" box="[151,298,295,321]" name="Saudi Arabia" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Saudi Arabia</collectingCountry>
